Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Boil a full #kettle{}. Trim the @green beans{80} and chop into thirds.

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} with @salt{1/4%tsp} on high heat. Add the @basmati rice{150} and cook for ~{12%minutes}.

Add the green beans to the pan halfway through cooking.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the saucepan.

While the rice cooks, pop the @diced butternut squash{300} onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, sprinkle over the @chermoula spice mix{2}, then toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden and cooked through, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

While everything roasts, crumble the @Greek style salad cheese{50}.

Pick the @mint{1} leaves from their stalks and roughly chop (discard the stalks).

Pop the @Greek style natural yoghurt{75} and half the mint into a small #bowl{}. Mix well, then set your mint yoghurt aside.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @harissa paste{50} (use less if you'd prefer things milder) and garlic. Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the cooked rice, beans and @vegetable stock paste{10}, then cook, stirring frequently, until combined and piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed, adding a splash of @water{splash} if it's a little dry.

Once roasted, stir the chermoula butternut through your pilaf. Taste and season again if needed.

Share the harissa pilaf between your #bowls{} and top with the crumbled Greek style salad cheese.

Sprinkle with the remaining mint, then finish with a dollop of mint yoghurt and a scattering of @toasted flaked almonds{15}.

Enjoy!